(43, 11, 6, 23, 30, 18, 18, 'he abode two days still', 'Waiting for Divine Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of waiting for God''s timing. In both passages, the act of waiting precedes a gracious or merciful response from the Lord.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 6, 23, 55, 8, 9, 'abode two days still in the same place', 'Divine Timing and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine timing in John 11:6, where Jesus waits two days, contrasting human expectations with God''s higher understanding in Isaiah 55:8-9. Both passages emphasize that God''s ways and thoughts are beyond human comprehension.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 6, 1, 22, 14, 14, NULL, 'Delay and Divine Provision', 'This connection highlights the theme of waiting for divine intervention. In John 11:6, the delay before Jesus acts parallels the anticipation of God''s provision in Genesis 22:14, where Abraham recognizes God''s timely assistance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 6, 1, 42, 24, 24, NULL, 'Emotional Responses in Crisis', 'This connection highlights the emotional responses of Jesus and Joseph during critical moments. Both passages depict a delay in action, with Jesus waiting two days and Joseph weeping before taking decisive steps.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 6, 40, 15, 22, 28, NULL, 'Delay and Faith in Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of delay in response to urgent needs. In John 11:6, Jesus waits two days before acting, while in Matthew 15:22-28, he initially does not respond to the Canaanite woman''s plea, emphasizing the testing of faith before healing occurs.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 7, 42, 9, 51, 51, 'Let us go into Judea again.', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize a decisive movement towards Jerusalem. In John, Jesus expresses a clear intention to return to Judea, while in Luke, he ''stedfastly set his face'' to go to Jerusalem, indicating a purposeful journey.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 7, 43, 10, 40, 42, 'Let us go into Judea again', 'Journey to Judea and Belief', 'This connection highlights the movement of Jesus as he transitions from a place of retreat to Judea, where he seeks to engage with those who may believe in him. Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in Jesus, as seen in the disciples'' willingness to follow him and the many who believed in him beyond Jordan.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 7, 44, 20, 22, 24, 'Let us go into Judea again', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'This connection highlights the theme of a journey to Jerusalem, where both Jesus and Paul are depicted as moving towards a significant mission despite foreseen challenges. Both passages emphasize a commitment to their respective ministries, reflecting determination in the face of adversity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 7, 44, 15, 36, 36, NULL, 'Call to Visit Brethren', 'This connection highlights the theme of returning to visit and support fellow believers. Both Jesus and Paul express a desire to go again to places where they have ministered.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 8, 43, 8, 59, 59, 'the Jews of late sought to stone thee', 'Threat of Stoning', 'This connection highlights the danger Jesus faced from the Jews, as both passages reference attempts to stone him. In John 11:8, the disciples express concern about returning to a place where stoning occurred, paralleling the event in John 8:59 where stones were taken up against him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 8, 43, 10, 31, 31, 'sought to stone thee', 'Threat of Stoning', 'Both passages emphasize the danger Jesus faced from the Jews, specifically their intent to stone him. The disciples'' concern in John 11:8 reflects the hostility mentioned in John 10:31.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 8, 40, 16, 21, 23, 'the Jews of late sought to stone thee', 'Fear of Jerusalem''s Danger', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' concern for Jesus'' safety in both passages. In John, they express fear of stoning, while in Matthew, Jesus reveals his impending suffering in Jerusalem, which Peter rebukes. Both reflect the tension between Jesus'' mission and the danger he faces.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 8, 44, 21, 12, 13, 'goest thou thither again', 'Courage in the Face of Danger', 'Both passages emphasize the willingness to face danger for the sake of faith. In John, the disciples express concern about returning to a place where Jesus was threatened, while in Acts, Paul shows readiness to go to Jerusalem despite warnings of danger.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 8, 19, 11, 1, 3, 'the Jews of late sought to stone thee', 'Trust Amidst Threats', 'Both passages emphasize the danger posed by the wicked and the need for trust in the Lord. John 11:8 reflects the disciples'' concern for Jesus'' safety, while Psalms 11:1-3 speaks to the fear of fleeing from threats. This connection highlights the theme of steadfastness in faith despite peril.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 8, 44, 20, 24, 24, NULL, 'Courage in the Face of Danger', 'This connection highlights the theme of courage in both passages. In John 11:8, the disciples express concern for Jesus'' safety, while Acts 20:24 shows Paul prioritizing his mission despite potential dangers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 8, 40, 23, 7, 7, NULL, 'Authority and Recognition in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in ministry. In John 11:8, the disciples express concern about Jesus'' safety among the Jews, while Matthew 23:7 discusses the desire for recognition as a Rabbi, reflecting the tension between authority and public perception.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 9, 43, 9, 4, 4, NULL, 'Day and Night Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''day'' as a time for action and visibility. The idea of working ''while it is day'' in John 9:4 connects to the assurance in John 11:9 that walking in the day prevents stumbling due to light.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 9, 43, 12, 35, 35, 'light of this world', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of walking in the light to avoid stumbling in darkness. The reference to ''light'' in both verses connects the idea of guidance and awareness in one''s path.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 9, 24, 31, 9, 9, 'walk in the day', 'Walking in Light and Safety', 'This connection highlights the theme of walking without stumbling. Both passages emphasize the importance of light and guidance, with Jesus indicating that walking in the day prevents stumbling, while Jeremiah assures that God leads His people in a straight way where they shall not stumble.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 9, 42, 13, 31, 33, 'walk in the day', 'Walking in the Day', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of walking in the day, which symbolizes clarity and purpose in Jesus'' mission. In John, Jesus speaks of walking in the light, while in Luke, He mentions the necessity of walking today and tomorrow, indicating His commitment to His work despite threats.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 9, 20, 3, 23, 23, 'stumbleth not, because he seeth the light', 'Walking Safely in Light', 'This connection highlights the theme of walking safely and not stumbling. Both passages emphasize the importance of light and guidance in one''s path, suggesting that awareness and understanding lead to safety.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 10, 20, 4, 18, 19, 'because there is no light in him', 'Light and Darkness Contrast', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness. John 11:10 mentions stumbling due to lack of light, while Proverbs 4:19 describes the wicked stumbling in darkness, highlighting the importance of light for guidance.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 10, 62, 2, 10, 11, 'light in him', 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness, illustrating how love and hatred affect one''s spiritual state. Walking in the light leads to clarity and stability, while walking in darkness results in stumbling and blindness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 10, 24, 13, 16, 16, 'stumbleth, because there is no light', 'Connection of Light and Darkness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of stumbling in darkness due to a lack of light. John 11:10 speaks of walking in the night and stumbling because of no light, while Jeremiah 13:16 warns of stumbling upon dark mountains when light is sought. This connection highlights the consequences of spiritual darkness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 10, 24, 20, 11, 11, 'stumbleth, because there is no light', 'Stumbling in Darkness and Light', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of stumbling due to a lack of light or support. In John 11:10, the absence of light leads to stumbling, while Jeremiah 20:11 assures that the Lord''s presence prevents the persecutors from prevailing, causing them to stumble instead.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 10, 21, 2, 14, 14, NULL, 'Wisdom and Darkness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between wisdom and foolishness, with the wise having light and understanding, while the fool walks in darkness. This connection highlights the consequences of one''s choices in relation to knowledge and insight.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 10, 19, 27, 2, 2, 'stumbleth, because there is no light', 'Stumbling in Darkness and Danger', 'This connection highlights the theme of stumbling due to a lack of light or guidance. Both passages emphasize the consequences of walking in darkness, leading to downfall or defeat.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 11, 27, 12, 2, 2, 'sleepeth; but I go, that I may awake him out of sleep', 'Resurrection and Awakening Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of awakening from sleep, as both passages refer to those who sleep and the act of awakening. John 11:11 speaks of Lazarus sleeping and being awakened, while Daniel 12:2 discusses those who sleep in the dust awakening to different fates.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 11, 43, 11, 13, 13, 'sleepeth', 'Connection of Sleep and Death', 'This connection highlights the metaphor of sleep as a representation of death. Both passages emphasize Jesus'' reference to Lazarus'' state, where ''sleep'' signifies a deeper reality of death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
